%U A396082 257,269,271,277,281,283,293,307,313,317,331,337,349,353,367,373,379,389
%N A396082 Primes p such that A381466(2p) > 2p.
%C A396082 We conjecture that this sequence is infinite. If it is, then each term multiplied by two is an addition step of A381466. This would be an example of a "reasonably describable" infinite set of even addition steps. This is relevant, as we have proven that all odd primes and their squares are addition steps of A381466, so we know about two infinite families of odd addition steps. If there were infinitely many terms of a(n) that are adjacent to odd primes or their squares, then that would prove that there are infinitely many 2's or 3's in A394761.
